03792nam a22006255i 9781442682573DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20172004onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426825737 a10.3138/97814426825732doi  a(DE-B1597)483160  a(OCoLC)1004868399  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aHIS0200002bisacsh04a769/.499453107/071 aWilson, Bronwen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe World in Venice :bPrint, the City, and Early Modern Identity /cBronwen Wilson. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2004  a1 online resource (490 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Book and Print Culture00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIllustrations -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. From Myth to Metropole: Sixteenth-Century Printed Maps of Venice -- tChapter 2. Costume and the Boundaries of Bodies -- tChapter 3. Allegory, Order, and the Singular Event -- tChapter 4. Reproducing the Individual: Likeness and History in Printed Portrait Books -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPositing a dynamic relationship between print culture and social experience, Bronwen Wilson's The World in Venice focuses on the printed image during a century of profound transformation. City views, costume illustrations, events, and portraits of locals and foreigners are brought together to show how printmakers responded to an expanding image of the world in Renaissance Venice, and how, in turn, prints influenced the ways in which individuals thought about themselves.Woodcuts and engravings of cities and inhabitants of Europe, and those of distant lands, initiated a sudden and pervasive experience with alterity that redefined the relations of Europeans to the world. By condensing the world into pictures, print enabled a radically novel and vicarious experience of others. Wilson explores the overlapping and evolving relations between space, vision, print, and identity, and engages with current scholarly debates concerning ethnicities, gender and geography, copies and originals, travel, nationhood, fashion, urban life, visuality, and the body.Venice was one of the largest cities in Renaissance Europe, a trading crossroads, and a centre of print. The World in Venice shows how Venetian identity came to be envisioned within the growing global context that print constructed for it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Italy.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268257340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442682573423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442682573.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK